                <div class="relative min-w-0 w-full grid grid-cols-1 xl:grid-cols-[auto_--spacing(56)]">
                    <div class="relative flex-auto min-w-0 px-0 lg:ps-outer xl:px-16 py-16 lg:pb-5">
                        <div class="absolute -z-10 top-0 start-0 w-full h-40 bg-grid-gray-950 dark:bg-grid-gray-50 bg-grid-size-10 dark:bg-grid-size-10 mask-radial mask-position-to-80% mask-opacity-to-20% opacity-5 dark:opacity-10 pointer-events-none"></div>

                        <article data-sx-toc-src class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
                            <header>
                                <span class="badge inline-flex mb-3">
                                    10 min read
                                </span>

                                <h1 id="___TOCBOT___" class="-my-3 text-4xl text-pretty font-bold tracking-tight leading-tighter">
                                    <span class="inline-flex py-3 text-gray-950 dark:bg-linear-to-br from-gray-100 from-50% to-background-dark dark:bg-clip-text dark:text-transparent">
                                        Why is ReLU a Non-Linear Activation Function?
                                    </span>
                                </h1>                                    

                                    <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-pretty">The most intuitive guide to ReLU activation function ever.</p>

                            </header>

                                <div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-purple" style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                                    <div class="kg-callout-emoji">👉</div>
                                    <div id="parity-banner-container-lesson" class="kg-callout-text" data-has-access="false" style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 1.1em;"></div>
                                </div>
                                <style>
                                    #parity-banner-container-lesson a {
                                        color: #0066cc;
                                    }
                                </style>
                                <hr style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">

                            <div class="overflow-x-hidden mt-8 content">
                                <h2 id="introduction"><strong>Introduction</strong></h2><p>The true strength of a neural network comes from activation functions. They allow the model to learn non-linear complex relationships between inputs and outputs.</p><p>That is why they are considered a core component of all neural networks.</p><p>There are many activation functions one can use to learn non-linear patterns. These include Sigmoid, Tanh, etc.</p><p>But among all popular choices, many folks struggle to intuitively understand ReLU's power.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/relu-graph-1-1.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="638" height="400" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/06/relu-graph-1-1.jpeg 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/relu-graph-1-1.jpeg 638w"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">ReLU activation function</span></figcaption></figure><p>With its seemingly linear shape, calling it a non-linear activation function isn't intuitive.</p><p>An obvious question is: "<strong>How does ReLU allow a neural network to capture non-linearity?</strong>"</p><p>If you have been in that situation, let me help.</p><p>By the end of this blog, you will have an intuitive understanding of ReLU, how it works, and why it is so effective.</p><p>Let's begin!</p><h2 id="why-activation-functions"><strong>Why activation functions?</strong></h2><p>Before understanding ReLU's effectiveness, let's understand the purpose of using activation functions.</p><p>Imagine a neural network <strong>without any activation functions</strong>.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/image-54.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="367" height="313"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Neural network with one hidden layer</span></figcaption></figure><p>The input $x$ is multiplied by a set of weights $W_{1}$ and a bias $b_{1}$ is added.</p><p>$$ Z_{1} = W_{1} \cdot x + b_{1} $$</p><p>The above output is then passed to the next layer for transformation using a new set of weights $W_{2}$ and biases $b_{2}$.</p><p>$$ Z_{2} = W_{2} \cdot Z_{1} + b_{2} $$</p><p>This process goes on and on until the output layer.</p><p>In such a scenario, the neural network would essentially be a series of linear transformations and translations stacked together:</p><ul><li>First, the weight matrix $W$ applies a linear transformation.</li><li>Next, the bias term $b$ translates the obtained output.</li></ul><p>Thus, without activation functions, the network never captures any non-linear patterns.</p><p>To understand better, consider the following 2D dataset: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/relu_blog1-2.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="500" height="506"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Linearly inseparable circles data</span></figcaption></figure><p>Clearly, the data is linearly inseparable.</p><p>Next, we will replicate the transformation done by a neural network. For simplicity and to create a visualization, we'll do these in 2D.</p><p>Let the weight matrix and bias be:</p><p>$$ W = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -2 \\ -2 &amp; 2 \\ \end{bmatrix} \ ; \ b = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ \end{bmatrix} $$</p><p>The transformation is visualized below:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/relu-blog-linear.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1302" height="922" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/07/relu-blog-linear.jpg 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w1000/2023/07/relu-blog-linear.jpg 1000w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/relu-blog-linear.jpg 1302w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Linear transformation of linearly inseparable circles data</span></figcaption></figure><p>As shown, the entire transformation does nothing but scales, rotates and shifts the data. However, linear inseparability remains unaffected.</p><p>The same is true for a neural network without activations.</p><p>No matter how many layers we add, the output will always be a linear transformation of the input.</p><p>In fact, one can squish all the linear transformations into a single weight matrix $W$, as shown below:</p><p>$$ W_{k} \cdot (W_{k-1} (\dots (W_{2} \cdot (W_{1}\cdot x))))  \rightarrow Wx$$</p><p>The absence of an activation function severely limits the expressiveness and modeling power of the neural network. As a result, the network can only learn linear relationships.</p><p>We can also verify this experimentally:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.09.56-PM-1.gif" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1268" height="752" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.09.56-PM-1.gif 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w1000/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.09.56-PM-1.gif 1000w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.09.56-PM-1.gif 1268w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Training neural network with linear activation function (created using </span><a href="https://playground.tensorflow.org/?ref=dailydoseofds.com" rel="noopener"><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Tensorflow Playground</span></a><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">)</span></figcaption></figure><p>Despite having sufficient layers, each with many neurons, the decision boundary stays linear at every epoch.</p><p>However, by adding an activation function (Tanh, in this case), the network progressively learns a non-linear decision boundary:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.15.24-PM.gif" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1268" height="752" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.15.24-PM.gif 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w1000/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.15.24-PM.gif 1000w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/Screen-Recording-2023-06-26-at-7.15.24-PM.gif 1268w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Training neural network with Tanh activation function (created using </span><a href="https://playground.tensorflow.org/?ref=dailydoseofds.com" rel="noopener"><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Tensorflow Playground</span></a><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">)</span></figcaption></figure><p>This explains the importance of activation functions.</p><p>To reiterate...</p><p>To model non-linear problems, there must be some non-linearity in the networks. Activation functions do precisely that!</p><h2 id="why-relu"><strong>Why ReLU?</strong></h2><p>Before understanding how ReLU adds non-linearity to a neural network, let's consider why we typically prefer ReLU over other activation functions.</p><p>In other words, let's look at some advantages of using ReLU over its contenders.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-yellow"><div class="kg-callout-emoji">👉</div><div class="kg-callout-text">Feel free to skip this part if you are well-versed with the advantages of ReLU.</div></div><h3 id="1-relu-is-computationally-efficient-both-forward-and-backward"><strong>#1) ReLU is computationally efficient (both forward and backward)</strong></h3><p>ReLU involves a simple mathematical operation free from complex transformations such as exponentials, sinusoids, etc.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/equation_o-1-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="500" height="109"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">ReLU activation function</span></figcaption></figure><p>Therefore, it can be computed quickly and easily during a forward pass.</p><p>Moreover, gradient computation performed during the backward pass is equally simple.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/equation_backrelu.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="500" height="97"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The gradient of the ReLU activation function</span></figcaption></figure><p>Thus, computational efficiency makes ReLU a preferred choice, especially for large neural networks with many parameters.</p><h3 id="2-relu-contributes-to-dropout"><strong>#2) ReLU contributes to Dropout</strong></h3><p>Overfitting is a common problem in neural networks. <a href="https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~rsalakhu/papers/srivastava14a.pdf?ref=dailydoseofds.com">Dropout</a> is a regularization technique that randomly drops (or zeros-out) units from a neural network during training.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/image-58.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="825" height="238" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/07/image-58.png 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/image-58.png 825w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Dropout in neural network</span></figcaption></figure><p>This prevents units from co-adapting excessively and encourages the network to learn more diverse and robust features.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/equation_o-1-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="500" height="109"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">ReLU activation function</span></figcaption></figure><p>As depicted in the above equation, by using ReLU, a neuron with a negative activation is turned off.</p><p>Therefore, ReLU, in a way, contributes to Dropout and adds a bit more regularization to the network.</p><h3 id="3-relu-avoids-gradient-vanishing"><strong>#3) ReLU avoids gradient vanishing</strong></h3><p>There's a common problem with activation functions such as Sigmoid (or Tanh).</p><p>At times, the gradients may become very small.</p><p>For instance, for large positive and negative inputs, the gradient of the Sigmoid curve is small.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/image_o-14.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1035" height="771" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/06/image_o-14.png 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w1000/2023/06/image_o-14.png 1000w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/06/image_o-14.png 1035w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Sigmoid has a small gradient for extreme inputs</span></figcaption></figure><p>Thus, gradients may become increasingly smaller during backpropagation, leading to insignificant parameter updates.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/image-60.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="601" height="344" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/07/image-60.png 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/image-60.png 601w"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Gradient descent with small gradient updates</span></figcaption></figure><p>Vanishing gradients make it difficult for the network to learn, especially the initial layers of the network.</p><p>ReLU, on the other hand, produces a constant gradient for positive inputs, thereby avoiding vanishing gradients. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/Screenshot-2023-07-05-at-6.20.19-AM.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1714" height="1111" srcset="https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w600/2023/07/Screenshot-2023-07-05-at-6.20.19-AM.png 600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w1000/2023/07/Screenshot-2023-07-05-at-6.20.19-AM.png 1000w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/size/w1600/2023/07/Screenshot-2023-07-05-at-6.20.19-AM.png 1600w, https://storage.ghost.io/c/3f/df/3fdf6ed2-17ac-4b12-a693-8078bd13e748/content/images/2023/07/Screenshot-2023-07-05-at-6.20.19-AM.png 1714w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The gradient of the ReLU activation function</span></figcaption></figure><p>This results in faster learning.</p><hr><h2 id="proof"><strong>Proof</strong></h2><p>Now that we understand what makes ReLU advantageous over other activation functions, we'll see how ReLU acts as a non-linear activation function.</p>

